<BaseLayout
  title="Severance Pay FAQ | severancepayestimator.com"
  description="Answers to the most common questions about severance pay — from legal requirements and taxes to negotiation and what to do before you sign."
>
  <h1>Severance Pay FAQ</h1>
  <p class="byline">Reviewed by <strong>Sloan Whitfield, SHRM-CP</strong>. Updated May 2026.</p>

  <dl>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <dt>Is severance pay required by law?</dt>
      <dd>
        No. Under federal law, private employers are generally not required to provide severance pay. The Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA) sets minimum wage and overtime rules but says nothing about severance. However, there are important exceptions: if your employer has a written severance policy, a contractual obligation in your offer letter or employment agreement, or a plan subject to ERISA, they may be legally required to follow those terms. The WARN Act also creates a back-pay remedy (up to 60 days) for mass layoffs without proper notice — which functions like mandatory severance in qualifying situations.
      </dd>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <dt>How is severance pay taxed?</dt>
      <dd>
        Severance is generally treated as ordinary income and is subject to federal income tax, Social Security tax (up to the annual wage base), and Medicare tax. If your employer classifies your severance as "supplemental wages" (which is common), they may withhold at the flat supplemental rate of 22% for amounts up to $1 million, rather than using your standard withholding. This can result in underwithholding or overwithholding depending on your marginal rate. State income tax also applies in most states. See our full <a href="/guides/severance-pay-tax-guide">Severance Tax Guide</a> for more detail.
      </dd>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <dt>Can I negotiate my severance package?</dt>
      <dd>
        Yes, in most cases. Even if your employer presents a package as "standard" or "final," there is typically room to negotiate — especially for mid-level and senior employees. Common negotiation targets include: additional weeks of base pay, extended COBRA subsidy, outplacement services, equity vesting acceleration, and a reference letter. The key is to negotiate before you sign, during the review period. Once you sign the release of claims, your leverage disappears. Read our full guide on <a href="/guides/how-to-negotiate-severance">how to negotiate your severance package</a>.
      </dd>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <dt>What is a separation agreement?</dt>
      <dd>
        A separation agreement is a contract between you and your employer that governs the terms of your departure. It almost always includes a general release of claims — you agree not to sue the company for any employment-related claims (discrimination, wrongful termination, wage violations, etc.) in exchange for the severance payment. It may also include non-disparagement clauses, confidentiality provisions, non-compete and non-solicitation restrictions, and the specific payment schedule. You should read the entire agreement carefully and, ideally, have it reviewed by an employment attorney before signing.
      </dd>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <dt>What is the WARN Act and when does it apply?</dt>
      <dd>
        The federal WARN Act (Worker Adjustment and Retraining Notification Act) requires employers with 100 or more full-time employees to provide 60 calendar days' advance notice before a "plant closing" (affecting 50 or more employees at a single site) or a "mass layoff" (affecting either 500 or more employees, or 50–499 employees who represent at least 33% of the workforce at a site). If the employer fails to give proper notice, affected employees are entitled to back pay and benefits for each day of the violation, up to 60 days. Many states have their own "mini-WARN" laws with lower thresholds. See our <a href="/guides/warn-act-severance-guide">WARN Act guide</a> for more.
      </dd>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <dt>Can I collect unemployment insurance if I received severance?</dt>
      <dd>
        It depends on your state. Some states treat severance as "wages" and delay or reduce unemployment benefits by the number of weeks the severance covers. Others allow you to collect unemployment immediately regardless of severance received. California, for example, generally does not count lump-sum severance as wages for UI purposes, while states like Pennsylvania and New York may reduce benefits during the period covered by severance. Contact your state's Department of Labor to understand the rules that apply to you.
      </dd>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <dt>Can my employer take back severance after it's paid (clawback)?</dt>
      <dd>
        Yes, under certain circumstances. Most separation agreements include clawback provisions allowing the employer to recover severance if you violate the agreement — for example, by breaching the confidentiality clause, disparaging the company publicly, or taking a job with a competitor in violation of a non-compete. Some executive plans also include clawbacks triggered by restatement of financial results. Review any clawback language carefully before signing and understand exactly what conduct triggers recapture.
      </dd>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <dt>What happens to COBRA health insurance in a severance package?</dt>
      <dd>
        Under COBRA (the Consolidated Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act), you have the right to continue your employer-sponsored health coverage for up to 18 months after losing your job — but at the full premium, which includes the portion your employer previously subsidized. This can easily cost $600–$2,000 per month for an individual or family plan. Some severance packages include a COBRA subsidy, where the employer continues to pay some or all of the premium for a defined period (typically 3–6 months). This subsidy is a valuable negotiating point and can add thousands of dollars of real value to your package.
      </dd>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <dt>Can my employer include a non-compete in my severance agreement?</dt>
      <dd>
        Yes, and it is common. However, the enforceability of non-competes varies dramatically by state. California, North Dakota, Minnesota, and Oklahoma effectively ban employee non-competes. Other states enforce them if they are reasonable in scope, duration, and geography. A non-compete that restricts you from working in your field for two years in an entire metro area is likely overbroad in most jurisdictions. Before agreeing to any non-compete as part of a severance agreement, consult an employment attorney in your state to understand whether the restriction is enforceable and whether you can negotiate it down.
      </dd>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <dt>What should I do before signing a severance agreement?</dt>
      <dd>
        First, do not sign under pressure or rush to meet an artificial deadline. Under federal law (OWBPA), if you are 40 or older, you are entitled to at least 21 days to consider the agreement and 7 days to revoke it after signing. Younger workers should still take at least a few days to: (1) read the entire document carefully, (2) identify all the claims you are waiving, (3) calculate the value of what you are receiving vs. what you might be giving up, (4) consult an employment attorney, and (5) consider whether to negotiate. See our full checklist: <a href="/guides/what-to-do-before-signing-severance">What to Do Before Signing a Severance Agreement</a>.
      </dd>
    </div>
  </dl>

  <p class="disclaimer">
    FAQ answers are for general informational purposes only and do not constitute legal advice. Laws vary by state and individual circumstances. Consult a licensed employment attorney for guidance specific to your situation.
  </p>
</BaseLayout>
